Inflation in Europe has derailed on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was higher than forecast, after a rate of inflation of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, said the Bureau of Statistics of the European Community located in Luxembourg.
The official forecasts indicated only 3 per cent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the direct interest rate by saying that the decline in interest rates, with the rise in commodity prices and the fall in unemployment, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to maintain the rate of inflation below but close to two per cent.
According to an analyst, Catch 22 is for the ECB: "Inflation must be deterred" in order to stop having to intervene later on.
In Germany, the 3.3 per cent inflation rate is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off because of the rapid increase in food and energy prices.
The market shares of cereals have increased by 88% and soya prices have also reached the highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price increased by 52 per cent and, last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will increase from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009, it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, next 3-4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to decrease its direct rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of Fidesz supporters (the Alliance of Young Democrats) has increased significantly since December. Thus since 2002, it has currently had the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (the Institute of Surveys) has never previously found such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would be, because of the greatest determination of the voters of the opposition, more than two-thirds (71 per cent) of support against the support of one-fifth (20 per cent) for the Hungarian Socialist Party (MSZP).
According to the survey, the MDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) and the SZDSZ (Free Democrats Alliance) are below the parliamentary threshold: their support is two percent across the population.
On the one hand, some of the loyal voters voted, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 per cent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, with the proportion of those who felt that the country's economic situation was particularly serious had never been as high, with 41 per cent and 46 per cent supplementing the situation.
After the more optimistic outlook for the spring and summer of last year, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects aggravation and only one tenth expects an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of respondents, a majority never seen in Gallup's previous polls, found that the Prime Minister was doing his job rather bad than good.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent don't trust the Prime Minister and 27 percent the President of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that discontent with the Prime Minister can be addressed without change of government.
While, following the October riots, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, this rate currently represents only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) felt that the holding of new elections would be the solution to this situation.
To the question of the intention to vote, 60 per cent of the respondents replied that they would certainly vote and the additional 20 per cent said that they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to organize next Sunday", only 55 percent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent would probably participate. Following the current intentions, the referendum result would be no doubt.
74 percent of people would say no to tuition fees, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees and 84 percent would say no to hospital expenses.
When we look only at the same proportion of those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of the voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay costs.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by close to twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16% last year, unlike that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Napi Gazdaság Article (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, an increase of significantly more than a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
The prices, which had already flown into the major food stores last December, have no longer risen sharply compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the probed hypermarkets exceeded 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value in the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at the level of last year, but the prices of turkey nets, nuts and poppy have increased sharply.
In the shops, the price of flour and bread followed the KSH data (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread was found from 1 kilo to 139 forints only.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forks.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the bottle marked with two litres of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it only cost 257 forged the bottle included.
It only prevents this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and the least expensive Cora.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its 15 percent daily Cart while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent, respectively.
By comparing the most expensive basket of last year and the least expensive basket of this year, we see a 12 percent difference, while the difference between the least expensive basket of last year and the most expensive basket of this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by 1,480 forints on average.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1 206 forns, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate had already been noticed in the Christmas prices of last year.
This process made trade perplexed, hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply on products as long as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, it may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the prices of the Daily Cart evolved in such excessive way that the most expensive basket was higher than 1,720 forints at the value of 2006 while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the price of the most expensive basket was more than 1,630 forints than last year's and the prices of the least expensive ones increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By getting closer to the two Christmas seasons, we found a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer goods increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some diets of prime necessity, the statistical institute has found an increase in prices of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the Daily Cart of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already expensive last year, has hardly increased by more than 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the reports, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they were able to accept the brutal increase in prices by multinationals as well.
In the trade gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, most customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-term food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, important tails formed at the caisses of the three hypermarkets because the number of customers has increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to polling companies not even to reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals are saving disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
Hospital health conditions, insufficient beds, overcrowding of medical personnel do not help block infections, says the Chief Medical Officer of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals are also saving disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the János Hospital's trauma service.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected in a hospitalised man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident left the hospital but shortly after it had to return due to an MRSA infection and, since then, the doctors have not been able to perform an important operation because of the bacterium in their body.
Up to December 10 of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSAs, i.e. staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One third of the people are carriers of the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as angina, tonsilitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a bacteria that is well resistant to antibiotics that will rapidly proliferate under bad hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly patients, with small weights or with a weakened organism.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the hospital's daily routine.
Above all, we must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we cannot find only MRSA or we do not seek it, Tibor Nyulasi said.
SA is resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the care staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics suitable for treating them," Tibor Nyulasi said.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is non-moderate
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSAs could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and residences for elderly people, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It is important to know that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most of the cases are only seen if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strong recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the healing of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
The implementation of microbiological surveys is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals are saving disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash hands, to put gloves and protective masks. However, important gaps are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in the end of the epidemic, the patients should be away from each other at least 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, make savings on disinfectants, lack of nurses, the sick are numerous, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is lower demonstrablely or the proliferation of the pathogen may be blocked.
Government project against MRSAs
The treatment of MRSA is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why we are fighting all over this infection.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the impact of MRSAs.
According to the published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
Commissioner, author of a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness
The official record of the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement was prepared.
It may be excluded that the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has resigned from his post since, who has crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led to the state of drunkenness or scorn, announced Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Ministry of the Capital after the relative finding was made.
