EUR 400 million additional for infrastructure
János Veres, Minister of Finance of Hungary, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday with a total value of EUR 400 million for a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, with a credit contract worth EUR 100 million already signed by the parties. This time, the signed contract relates to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also covers the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, and the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties signed a €50 million contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope primarily as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the metro line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would reconsider the possible amendment of the initial contract once Hungary finalized the details of metro financing with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has totalled EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB shall grant its appropriations in accordance with the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment commission.
Bulgaria, a paradise for the EU real estate market
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to this Balkan country little mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market which is always the least expensive but which will soon become expensive?
Analysis from Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
At present, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and houses on the edge of the cheap sea.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, along the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly searching for a building in the region of Kavarna and Balcik as well.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also awaken the interest of investors and they are also growing to buy in the very cheap corner of Russia.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, the areas of commerce and offices promise the highest rate of depreciation.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of Europe's most attractive golf paradise and thus be a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
The more vigilant investors already buy in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time looking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, said Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old collapsed houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication opportunities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general to the local physician.
The second group includes secondary residence buyers (since last December Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving a medium or long-term value added.
The price of the capital's buildings continues to rise as a result of an ever-increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last five years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Waters, the meetings of professionals end Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after official opening, the negotiations of Ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians coming from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Road Map intended to define the efforts to be made after the emissions reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, there is strong discussion on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also noted that, for the time being, they did not want to discuss exact figures, but that they were ready to sign an agreement on the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions from 25 to 40 per cent from 1990 to 2020.
Another important issue at the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, without reducing emissions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund set out in the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of 16 members probably within the framework of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac es Profit (Market and Profit).
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for the Environment and Water Gábor Fodor confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as an admiral vessel in global efforts to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 by 20% compared to the level reached in 1990, regardless of the success of the signing of the ‘After 2012 Agreement’, and was ready to reduce it to 30% if the other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also prepared to make commitments tailored to their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries that were signatories to the Kyoto Protocol had a total reduction of 5.2 per cent, and all 15 EU members at that time had committed 8 per cent less.
Hungary has undertaken to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the 1985-1987 level, our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The challenge is great in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within the two-year period, if not the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments below the Kyoto Protocol values would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was highlighted in the new IPCC report, an international scientific body, which has obtained the Nobel Peace Prize of the United Nations, to deal with climate change.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in average Earth temperature of more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
The British army recruits on YouTube
British Army units report on the video-sharing site of recordings made during operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First, British Air Force (RAF) has been passionate about YouTube: special units in Afghanistan are loading video footage of Taliban operations since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the headquarters of the air force operations in Kandahar and are then transferred to London or the compatriots charge them on the Internet.
The political message is indispensable.
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and reports on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Department (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were passed on to the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to publicize the actual objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs almost nothing in relation to the usual advertisements for recruitment on television, communicated to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, and, on the other hand, it also inevitably carries a political message as it justifies in a special form the soundness of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans have made a game
The army is embarrassed because, apart from the videos composed and censored carefully, amateur videos have been placed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently been packing up for loading these videos.
The Americans recruit a little differently using the American's Army shooting game for free download. In this game the player can put himself directly instead of the soldiers in a more or less real simulation.
