Heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, Bad Arolsen's Nazi archives, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archives, stored on 27 km of lineage in Bad Arolsen, Hesse, were only available for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e., on an individual and adjective basis, upon the request of a former victim or his right-holders.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of the agreement by all States has been completed, and it has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research to be carried out "in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of camps and the state of health of forced workers," says Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, including Germany, opposed the opening of these documents to the public because of the sensitivity of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory work and, possibly, to provide proof of their detention, in order to open the way for compensation.
Again in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to await these documents," said Fr Wolfgang Benz, director of the Antisemitism Research Centre at Technische Universität in Berlin in 2006.
