Venus is the infernal twine of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like the Earth than we thought so far: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and windstorms at the poles, similar to those appearing in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are flashes on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has today provided proof of this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: the lightning on Venus burst at about 56 kilometers of cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous cyprine theory, the lightnings would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, a cornerstone of life.
This is not the case with Venus: "If life was there, it must have been at a very old date in history," says Sean Solomon of the "Carnegie Institution" in Washington.
There should not be much living today on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus is perhaps the infernal twine of the Earth, but it remains a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, who looks so much like the Earth in mass and dimension, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venezuelan research, since no probe was on its way to exploring this planet since the nineties.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" not only highlight the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighbouring planet are more than supposed to be at first glance.
Thus the researchers found, in addition to the windstorms already known at the north pole, a whirlwind of clouds at the south pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon recalls the air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Institute of Astrophysics Space and Physics Italian Cosmica.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The star-qualified planet of the evening or morning spins around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: one Venezuelan day lasts 243 Earthly days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, does not recall the Earth, scientists assume that both planets have formed under similar conditions.
On both sides, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost into space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has established itself on Earth in the form of carbonate, it constitutes on Venus most of the atmosphere.
