It's not Warhols' crates.
He who connects Sweden concepts and wooden boxes, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the ninety-ten Brillo-Boxes of "Stockholm Type" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxes of 1968 by Andy Warhol, the internal researches of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm result today in a disappointing result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", whose former director of the Pontus Hulten museum made a gift in 1995 at the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Type Stockholm", which circulate in the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and healing productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powdered soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - of the hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, samples of exposure.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time today speak of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auction sales.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum wrongly claimed that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol would then have given it to him.
Indeed, the 105 Hultén boxes were produced in Malmö in 1990 only for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
Warhol had already died on that date for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, next to the six Brillo-Boxes of the museum, three other Swedish private collections, of which two were made in Stockholm in 1968: their stratified panels were first printed and ponted, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies dating from 1990 reveals instead that the painting was directly applied without a layer of background on the stratified panels, using a roll of paint - moreover it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These caisses were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol's official list of Brillo-Boxes," says Moderna Museet Director Lars Nittve: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six caisses in its collection as copies/exposure materials."
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then, we've had an inexorable silence.
